<p>A first consultation is sometimes free and sometimes ฿300–฿1,000 (often credited against treatment). Two practical tips: never let "how much product" be decided by your budget rather than your face, and always ask whether the quoted price is per area, per unit or per syringe — that one question removes most billing surprises. If you're combining a beauty trip with a wider plan, our <a class="inline" href="plan-my-trip.html">trip planner</a> can help you slot consultations sensibly around your stay.</p>
<div class="callout tip">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-20"><use href="#pg-info"></use></svg></div>
<div><h4>Local tip · book the consult on a different day</h4><p>The best clinics don't pressure you to treat on the spot. Book a consultation, get the quote and product brand in writing, sleep on it, and return for treatment another day. A genuine clinic will happily wait; a salesy one won't — and that's useful information in itself.</p></div>
</div>
<h2 id="where">Where people go</h2>
<figure class="art-img">
<img alt="Aesthetic clinics pattaya 3 in Pattaya, Thailand" height="428" loading="lazy" src="../Pattaya-Tum-Gorseller-Resized/aesthetic-clinics-pattaya-3.webp" width="760"/>
<figcaption>Aesthetic Clinics Pattaya 3 – explore Pattaya's best spots</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Broadly, Pattaya's aesthetic care falls into two camps. The first is <strong>hospital-affiliated aesthetic centres</strong>, run inside or alongside private hospitals such as Bangkok Hospital Pattaya and Pattaya International Hospital. You pay more, but you get hospital-grade hygiene, clear oversight and a doctor-led model — a sensible default if it's your first time or you want injectables done conservatively. Many international visitors pair this with other care; if a beauty trip overlaps with dental work, our guide to <a class="inline" href="blog-dental-clinics-pattaya.html">dental clinics in Pattaya</a> applies the same licensing logic.</p>
<p>The second camp is <strong>established skin-clinic chains</strong> — names like Apex, Rajdhevee (Rajdhevee Skin), Nida, Pan and Wuttisak appear across Thailand and in Pattaya's malls and main roads. These are convenient, competitively priced and fine for laser, facials and routine skin work, but quality still depends on the individual branch and the doctor on duty that day. Wherever you go, the brand on the door matters less than the licence on the wall and the person holding the needle. Treat any clinic, chain or independent, by the same checklist below.</p>
<div class="verdict">
<div class="qv">
<div class="qv-label"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-shield-alert"></use></svg> Safest default</div>
<div class="qv-name">Hospital-affiliated centre</div>
<div class="qv-detail">Doctor-led · hospital hygiene · best for first-timers &amp; injectables</div>
</div>
<div class="qv">
<div class="qv-label"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-price"></use></svg> Best value for routine work</div>
<div class="qv-name">Established skin-clinic chain</div>
<div class="qv-detail">Laser, facials, peels · convenient · verify the branch &amp; doctor</div>
</div>
</div>
<h2 id="choose">How to choose a safe clinic</h2>
<p>This is the heart of the article. With injectables and lasers, <em>who</em> treats you and <em>what</em> they put in you matters more than the postcode or the price. Run through this checklist before you book — it's the same due diligence a careful local would do, and it costs you nothing but a few minutes.</p>
<div class="hood">
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-verified"></use></svg> Licence</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Confirm Thai MoPH / FDA licensing.</b> Legitimate clinics are licensed by Thailand's Ministry of Public Health and display a clinic-operation certificate. If you can't see one, ask — and walk if they're evasive.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-user"></use></svg> Who injects</div>
<div class="desc"><b>A doctor performs injectables — not a salon technician.</b> For Botox and fillers, insist on a registered doctor, ideally a board-certified dermatologist or someone with documented aesthetic training. Ask to meet them, not just the salesperson.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-first-aid"></use></svg> The product</div>
<div class="desc"><b>See genuine, branded product opened in front of you.</b> The box and sealed syringe should be shown and unsealed in your presence. Ask the brand name and note it. Refuse anything decanted from an unlabelled vial.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-book"></use></svg> Consultation</div>
<div class="desc"><b>A proper consultation comes first.</b> A real doctor asks about your health, medications and allergies, explains risks and aftercare, and sets realistic expectations — not "you'll look 10 years younger today".</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-check"></use></svg> Hygiene</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Clean room, single-use needles, sealed packaging.</b> Treatment areas should look clinical, not like a back room. Needles and cannulas come from sealed packs and are never reused.</div>
</div>
<div class="row">
<div class="area"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-16"><use href="#pg-phone"></use></svg> Aftercare</div>
<div class="desc"><b>Clear aftercare and a way to reach them.</b> You should leave with written aftercare and a contact for any reaction or concern. A clinic that disappears after payment is a red flag.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="callout">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-20"><use href="#pg-verified"></use></svg></div>
<div><h4>No pay-to-play</h4><p>Clinics can't buy a spot or rating on this page. We name categories and well-known chains as examples only, every recommendation is independent, and we never accept payment to feature a provider — the same standard across every <a class="inline" href="plan-my-trip.html">trip-planning guide</a>.</p></div>
</div>
<h2 id="avoid">What to avoid</h2>
<p>Most problems in Pattaya's aesthetics scene come from a small number of recognisable traps. Cut-price injectables are the biggest. A "deal" that's a fraction of the going rate usually means diluted toxin, an unlicensed injector, or counterfeit filler — and bad filler can cause infection, lumps, vascular blockage and, in rare cases, serious harm. Saving a few thousand baht is never worth that.</p>
<div class="callout warn">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-20"><use href="#pg-scam-alert"></use></svg></div>
<div><h4>Avoid cut-price "salon" injectables &amp; counterfeit product</h4><p><b>Do not get Botox or fillers from a beauty salon, spa, hotel room or anyone who can't show a clinic licence and a doctor.</b> Counterfeit and illegal fillers are a real risk at suspiciously cheap prices, and <b>"fly-in, treat same-day" pressure</b> exists to stop you doing exactly the checks above. Counterfeit toxin can be ineffective or unsafe; bad filler can cause infection, lumps or vascular complications that need urgent medical care. Always have a consultation first, see sealed branded product, confirm a doctor is treating you, and do your own due diligence before any needle goes in. If a price or a pitch feels too good to be true, leave.</p></div>
</div>
<p>A few smaller things to watch: avoid clinics that won't name the product brand, that decant filler from unlabelled containers, or that push you into "today only" packages far beyond what you came in for. And remember that more is not better — over-filled faces and frozen expressions are the hallmark of a clinic optimising for sales, not for you. For a calmer, lower-stakes introduction to Pattaya's wellness scene, our guides to the <a class="inline" href="blog-best-spa-pattaya.html">best spas in Pattaya</a> and the wider <a class="inline" href="pillar-wellness-beauty.html">wellness &amp; beauty pillar</a> are a gentler place to start.</p>
<h2 id="costs-context">Costs vs home &amp; medical tourism</h2>
<p>Honestly, Pattaya can be cheaper than the UK, US, Australia or much of Europe for the same treatments, which is why medical and "aesthetic tourism" exists here. Botox that might cost the equivalent of ฿20,000–฿40,000 per area at a Western clinic often sits in the ฿8,000–15,000 range here, and laser courses are similarly friendlier on the wallet. For routine, lower-risk work — laser hair removal, facials, peels — combining it with a holiday genuinely makes sense.</p>
<div class="money-grid">
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">Consultation</div><div class="val">฿0–1,000</div><p>Often free or credited against treatment at reputable clinics.</p></div>
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">Botox (one area)</div><div class="val">฿8,000–15,000</div><p>Brand- and dose-dependent; lasts 3–4 months.</p></div>
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">Filler (one syringe)</div><div class="val">฿12,000–25,000</div><p>Genuine HA only; lasts 6–18 months.</p></div>
<div class="money-card"><div class="label">Laser hair (course)</div><div class="val">฿9,000–24,000</div><p>6–8 sessions at ฿1,500–3,000 each, per area.</p></div>
</div>
<p>But be honest with yourself about the trade-offs. Anything with downtime, swelling or a possible complication — fillers, deeper lasers, HIFU — is best done where you'll be in the country long enough for a review and any follow-up, ideally a week or more. Don't book a complex injectable the day before you fly. Budget for aftercare, factor in that you won't have your usual doctor nearby, and never let a holiday deadline rush a medical decision. The savings are real; the risks of cutting corners to chase them are too.</p>
<h2 id="disclaimer">A note on expectations</h2>
<p>Results and risks vary from person to person, and no clinic can guarantee an outcome. A good doctor will tell you what's realistic for your skin, age and anatomy, and will sometimes recommend doing less — or nothing — rather than overselling. Temporary side effects like bruising, swelling and redness are normal with injectables and many lasers; persistent pain, spreading redness, vision changes or skin that turns pale or dusky after filler are not, and need prompt medical attention.</p>
<p>To be clear: <strong>this article is general information, not medical advice.</strong> It can't account for your health history, medications or individual risk. Before any treatment, consult a qualified doctor in person, ask questions until you're satisfied, and choose a licensed clinic even if it costs more. When it comes to your face and your health, the right verdict is simple — choose safety over price, every time.</p>
<!-- FAQ -->
<h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq">
<div class="faq-item open">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">How much does Botox cost in Pattaya? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">As an indicative 2026 range, Botox in Pattaya is roughly ฿8,000–15,000 per treatment area, though some clinics price per unit instead. The exact cost depends on the brand of toxin, how many units you need and the doctor's experience. Always ask whether the quote is per area or per unit, and be wary of prices far below the going rate — in injectables, very cheap usually means diluted or counterfeit product.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">Are aesthetic clinics in Pattaya safe? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">The best ones are genuinely safe — Pattaya has licensed, doctor-led aesthetic clinics, including hospital-affiliated centres with hospital-grade hygiene. Safety comes down to choosing well: confirm the clinic is licensed by Thailand's Ministry of Public Health, that a registered doctor performs injectables, and that you see sealed, branded product. Avoid beauty salons offering cut-price injectables, and do your own due diligence before booking.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">Should I get Botox or fillers from a beauty salon to save money? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">No. Botox and dermal fillers are medical procedures and should only be done in a licensed clinic by a qualified doctor. Salons offering cut-price injectables are a serious risk — counterfeit or diluted product and unqualified injectors can cause infection, lumps and rare but serious complications. The small saving is never worth the potential harm.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">How do I know a Pattaya clinic uses genuine product? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">Ask to see the product's box and sealed syringe, and have it opened in front of you so you can read the brand name. Reputable clinics do this without being asked and will tell you exactly which brand they use. Refuse any filler or toxin decanted from an unlabelled vial, and treat reluctance to show packaging as a reason to leave.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">Is it worth doing aesthetic treatments in Pattaya as a tourist? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">For lower-risk work like laser hair removal, facials and peels, it can be excellent value and easy to combine with a holiday. For injectables, deeper lasers or HIFU, only do it if you'll be in town long enough for a review and any follow-up — ideally a week or more — and never the day before you fly. Build in time and budget for aftercare, and don't let a travel deadline rush a medical decision.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="faq-item">
<button class="faq-q" type="button">Can a clinic guarantee how I'll look after treatment? <span aria-hidden="true" class="ico">+</span></button>
<div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner">No reputable clinic guarantees a specific outcome, because results and risks vary by individual. A good doctor sets realistic expectations, explains possible side effects and may recommend doing less rather than more. This article is general information, not medical advice — always consult a qualified doctor in person before any treatment.</div></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="callout">
<div class="ic"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="pg-icon is-20"><use href="#pg-shield-alert"></use></svg></div>
<div><h4>The bottom line</h4><p>Pattaya has excellent, licensed aesthetic clinics and some genuinely risky ones, and the difference rarely shows in the price tag. Confirm the licence, insist on a doctor for any injectable, see sealed branded product, and never let a cheap deal or a holiday deadline rush you. This is general information, not medical advice — consult a qualified doctor and <strong>choose safety over price, every time</strong>. When you're ready, our <a class="inline" href="plan-my-trip.html">trip planner</a> and <a class="inline" href="pillar-wellness-beauty.html">wellness &amp; beauty guide</a> can help you fit it sensibly into your stay.</p></div>
</div>
