"description": "Hyaluronic-acid filler for lips, cheeks, chin and jawline volume; lasts 6–18 months"}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "Laser hair removal", "description": "Course of 6–8 sessions to reduce unwanted hair; one of the lower-risk treatments"}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 4, "name": "Pico / IPL pigmentation", "description": "Laser and light treatment to fade sun spots, melasma and dullness over several sessions"}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 5, "name": "HIFU skin tightening", "description": "Non-surgical ultrasound lift along the jaw and neck with gradual results"}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 6, "name": "Profhilo &amp; bio-remodelling", "description": "Injectable skin-quality treatment for hydration and firmness rather than volume"}]}, {"@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question", "name": "How much does Botox cost in Pattaya?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "As an indicative 2026 range, Botox in Pattaya is roughly ฿8,000–15,000 per treatment area, though some clinics price per unit instead. The exact cost depends on the brand of toxin, how many units you need and the doctor's experience. Always ask whether the quote is per area or per unit, and be wary of prices far below the going rate — in injectables, very cheap usually means diluted or counterfeit product."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Are aesthetic clinics in Pattaya safe?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The best ones are genuinely safe — Pattaya has licensed, doctor-led aesthetic clinics, including hospital-affiliated centres with hospital-grade hygiene. Safety comes down to choosing well: confirm the clinic is licensed by Thailand's Ministry of Public Health, that a registered doctor performs injectables, and that you see sealed, branded product. Avoid beauty salons offering cut-price injectables, and do your own due diligence before booking."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Should I get Botox or fillers from a beauty salon to save money?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "No. Botox and dermal fillers are medical procedures and should only be done in a licensed clinic by a qualified doctor. Salons offering cut-price injectables are a serious risk — counterfeit or diluted product and unqualified injectors can cause infection, lumps and rare but serious complications. The small saving is never worth the potential harm."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How do I know a Pattaya clinic uses genuine product?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Ask to see the product's box and sealed syringe, and have it opened in front of you so you can read the brand name. Reputable clinics do this without being asked and will tell you exactly which brand they use. Refuse any filler or toxin decanted from an unlabelled vial, and treat reluctance to show packaging as a reason to leave."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Is it worth doing aesthetic treatments in Pattaya as a tourist?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "For lower-risk work like laser hair removal, facials and peels, it can be excellent value and easy to combine with a holiday. For injectables, deeper lasers or HIFU, only do it if you'll be in town long enough for a review and any follow-up — ideally a week or more — and never the day before you fly. Build in time and budget for aftercare, and don't let a travel deadline rush a medical decision."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Can a clinic guarantee how I'll look after treatment?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "No reputable clinic guarantees a specific outcome, because results and risks vary by individual. A good doctor sets realistic expectations, explains possible side effects and may recommend doing less rather than more. This article is general information, not medical advice — always consult a qualified doctor in person before any treatment."}}]}]$b$);
